<TITLE> Stocks shrug off losses </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, July 30 (bdnews24.com) -- Stocks shrugged off two-day losses Monday, triggered by a sharp surge in insurance shares after some companies claimed an increase in their half-yearly earnings. Bank, pharmaceuticals and leather and footwear stocks injected extra vigour into the market. Insurers began rallying on expectations for better earnings after Green Delta Insurance announced a 68.7 percent rise and Nitol Insurance had posted a 103 percent rise in half-yearly earnings. Most banks went up. But the banks that announced half-yearly earnings Monday finished with lower gains. Power stocks which have been trading on the spot market closed mixed as DESCO gained but Summit Power and Power Grid Company of Bangladesh lost. Apex stocks continued rallying since Apex Footwear declared half-yearly profit growth of 43 percent. Apex Footwear added 12.48 percent. GQ Ball Pen climbed 18.94 percent. The DGEN or general index rallied 35.50 points or 1.48 percent to 2425.99. The DSI or all-share price index grew 29.56 points or 1.52 percent to 1963.12. The DSE-20 blue chip index moved up 36.38 points or 1.65 percent to 2237.22. Gainers beat losers 140 to 60. Some 16 issues remained unchanged. Turnover rose to Tk 2.07 billion from Sunday's Tk 1.93 billion. All the major indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange finished upbeat, sending 106 issues to the gainers' pavilion. Sixty-seven issues lost. Turnover reached Tk 308.79 billion from Tk 250.20 million. A total of 28 scrips held steady. Square Pharma, Southeast Bank and UCBL ruled the turnover board on the DSE. Square Pharma had previously announced a plan to raise its authorised capital up to Tk 5.0 billion from the existing Tk 1.0 billion. Buoyed by foreign deals, Southeast Bank added 3.69 percent to Tk 589.75. UCBL climbed 6.90 percent to Tk 3562.25 on anticipation of holding its annual general meetings pending since 1997. Prime Bank ended at Tk 789.5, up 3.30 percent. National Bank advanced 5.06 percent to Tk 1017. bd
